message: This morning I met with Holley Coil from NBC/Telemundo and Janet Rodriguez of Univision to discuss goals for the new 115th Congress. All Members of Congress will be officially sworn in today in Washington. You can watch a live broadcast on C-SPAN: http://cs.pn/2iErVac

Today I was sworn into the 115th Congress. As your congressman, I will make sure to work with both Democrats and Republicans in Congress to represent all of my constituents and communities in District 28. Read more: http://bit.ly/2iFAKjO

Today, my friends, Vicente Gonzalez for U.S. Congress, Congressman Filemon Vela and I were sworn into the 115th Congress with a promise to represent our constituents, including our distinct parts of Hidalgo County. Read more: http://bit.ly/2iMMYEF
This morning, I met with President Obama and House Democrats about the importance of keeping the Affordable Care Act #ACA, which has given millions of previously uninsured Americans health coverage
Before the #ACA, Americans with pre-existing conditions could be denied or charged more for their health care coverage #ACAWorks
This morning I caught up with my friend and former Blue Dog colleague, Senator Joe Donnelly to discuss the importance of the #ACA.
Great speaking with Tsi-Tsi-Ki Félix of Perspectiva Nacional and Sabrina de Santiago of the Center for American Progress to discuss the legislative agenda in the 115th Congress
Today I stand with Members of the Congressional Hispanic Caucus to represent our constituents in the 115th Congress.
A U.S. intelligence community report on Russian activities released today says Putin ‘ordered’ effort to undermine faith in U.S. presidential election process.
I’m saddened by the news of the passing of San Antonio’s retired archbishop Patrick Flores, our nation’s first Mexican-American bishop. #RIP http://bit.ly/2jmQrJo

Today I spoke with Fox News about border security and the impracticality of a border wall.

Foreign interference in elections is unacceptable, which is why I have co-sponsored legislation, the Protecting Our Democracy Act, H.R. 356, to create a bipartisan, independent commission to investigate #RussianHacking to influence our presidential election using computer hacking and “fake news” reports. #ProtectingOurDemocracy

I invite all high school students, parents, teachers and counselors to attend our Service Academy informational session this Sunday in San Antonio. The session will provide details for those who are interested in attending one of our nation's five prestigious service academies: U.S. Military Academy at West Point, U.S. Naval Academy, U.S. Merchant Marine Academy, U.S. Coast Guard Academy and the U.S. Air Force Academy. A nomination from a member of Congress is required to apply to one of these prestigious institutions.   The informational session will take place Sunday, March 5, from 2:00 p.m. to 4:00 p.m. at the University of Texas at San Antonio (UTSA). Please see flyers below for more information.

My statement on the Omnibus Appropriations Bill:

#Trumpcare would gut protections for Americans with pre-existing conditions & drive up costs for millions. I opposed it the last time it was almost introduced, just weeks ago. I hope my Republican colleagues do not waste our time on this again. We need to focus on funding the government, and not repeat old health care fights again.

On the House floor today, I praised the Omnibus Appropriations bill, a bipartisan compromise that's good for #TX28.  http://cuellar.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=401153

#TrumpCare would be a disaster for the people of Texas.  I represent one of the highest uninsured populations in Congress. This bill hurts the most vulnerable to help the most powerful. It gives the richest 400 Americans (including the President and most of his Cabinet) an average $7 million tax cut by cutting Medicaid for poor children. That’s not what my constituents in Texas sent me to Congress to do.
The Congressional Budget Office has not had a chance to score #TrumpCare, so we don’t even know what it will cost. I am listening to my constituents and voting NO.
My statement now that the House has passed #TrumpCare:  I hope the Senate rejects this bill.

Response to the President’s budget proposal:  “This budget has big gifts for the rich, big cuts for the poor.  The American people have made themselves clear. They want responsible, efficient government spending, with smart investments in programs that work.   Instead, the President has proposed a bizarre, ideological budget. His reckless cuts would cut thriving, successful programs to pay for tax cuts for millionaires – instead of the small businesses that really need them. He wants to slash the basic programs that keep Texas drinking water clean, stop diseases from spreading, and care for vulnerable seniors.  Of the areas with the greatest percentage of residents on food stamps, 7 out of 10 voted for President Trump, hoping he would help them achieve a better life. Yet instead of investing in economic opportunities, he is threatening to make even less food available to our poorest families – including his voters.   Fortunately, the President does not control the federal budget. Congress does. I work with my colleagues on the Appropriations Committee to craft a reasonable, bipartisan budget that serves all Americans, encourages job creation, and protects veterans and seniors.”

Customs and Border Protection (CBP) is facing a staffing deficit of more than 3,000 positions. That puts our homeland security at risk. One reason for this dangerous shortage: applicants for every single law enforcement position must take a polygraph examination. Even current and former law enforcement and military members with Secret and Top Secret security clearances, must go through this laborious and failure-prone process.  The Anti-Border Corruption Reuthorization Act of 2017 would streamline the hiring process for current ‘cleared’ federal employees, law enforcement, or military members to join CBP after their background check, without having to go through a redundant polygraph. This is a common-sense measure to solve an obvious problem, make a government procedure more efficient, and secure our homeland.

When a commercial truck carrying produce crosses our southern border, it undergoes strict inspections for health and safety. If a bug causes concern, sometimes inspectors need to send it to a lab for more testing – all the way in Washington, DC. In the meantime, that truck’s cargo often spoils.   We could make this process more efficient, avoid food waste, prevent food-borne illness, and save businesses money, if we just had more lab capacity right at the border. That’s my plan to fix this problem.

“To all of my constituents in Texas’ 28th District, I wanted to personally notify you that Tropical Storm Harvey is now forecasted to be a major Hurricane, with maximum sustained winds of up to 80 mph. I urge all of you-- and everybody else in the hurricane’s path--to heed the advice of the National Weather Service, the National Hurricane Center, and local authorities. Please note that structural damages to sturdy buildings--some with complete roof and wall failure-- are possible. Flooding, high winds, and rainfall amounts of up to 15-20 inches are also possible. PLEASE make preparations today, as the winds will likely be too high to make proper preparations tomorrow. I am working diligently with FEMA and the Governor’s Office on proper preparation and response.  Stay safe and err on the side of caution.”   For more information on Hurricane Harvey, please visit: http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/news/AL092017_key_messages.png For more information on the affected areas, please visit: http://www.weather.gov/crp/ For more advice on how to deal with emergencies please visit: http://www.redcross.org/get-help/how-to-prepare-for-emergencies/mobile-apps

Today, I joined Laredo Mayor Pete Saenz, Nuevo Laredo Mayor Enrique Rivas Cuellar, Tamaulipas Secretary for Economic Development Carlos Talacon, Mexican Consul Carolina Zaragoza and others at Texas A&M International University to announce a binational effort to encourage our communities to provide help and support to the victims of yesterday’s devastating earthquake in Mexico.

I have spoken with Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto’s office and communicated with both the U.S. Ambassador to Mexico, Roberta Jacobson, and Mexico’s Ambassador to the United States, Gerónimo Gutiérrez, to offer my condolences and see how the United States can further provide humanitarian assistance to those affected by yesterday’s earthquake in Mexico City.  Hablé con la oficina del Presidente Enrique Peña Nieto, la Embajadora de Estados Unidos en México, Roberta Jacobson, y el Embajador de México en Estados Unidos, Gerónimo Gutiérrez, para enviar mis condolencias y para asegurarle que le daré seguimiento a la ayuda humanitaria que Estados Unidos le puede proporcionar a los afectados del sismo en su capital.

For years, I have been the leading Democrat in the House, advocating for the export of U.S. crude oil. Now, the U.S. is on track to pump more crude than Saudi Arabia by the middle of next year, assuming OPEC’s biggest producer keeps output at its current level. Based on an article published by Bloomberg, the U.S. will reach 9.99 million barrels a day in May, according to the Energy Information Administration. Saudi Arabia produced 9.97 million barrels a day in November.   Read more information regarding the topic here: https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2017-opec-timeline/
